sentence: Crude dips as U.S. inventories make surprising gains .

Investing.com - Crude oil futures fell in Asian trading on Thursday after the U.S. government revealed that weekly crude stockpiles rose more than expected , fueling fears demand for fuels and energy in the world 's largest economy may be slipping .

On the New York Mercantile Exchange , light , sweet crude futures for delivery in October traded at USD96 .98 a barrel on Thursday , down 0.03 % , off from a session high of USD97 .00 and up from an earlier session low of USD96 .94 .

The U.S. Energy Information Administration said in its weekly report that U.S. crude oil inventories rose by 1.99 million barrels in the week ended September 7 , defying expectations for a decline of 2.59 million barrels .
Total U.S. crude oil inventories stood at 359.1 million barrels as of last week .
Total motor gasoline inventories decreased by 1.18 million barrels , compared to expectations for a decline of 1.60 million barrels .
The U.S. is the world 's largest consumer of oil , responsible for almost 22 % of global oil demand .
The commodity did see support on news that a German court upheld the constitutionality of the country 's participation in eurozone financial rescue packages .

The constitutional court ruling in Germany gives Berlin the green light to ratify the European Stability Mechanism , the continent 's bailout fund , which will open the door for the European Central Bank to roll out its sovereign bond purchasing program .
Approval of the ESM aims to firewall and extinguish the European debt crisis .
Failure to ratify the ESM would have sparked fears the eurozone would face stronger headwinds or even crisis , which would cut into demand for crude , a growth-sensitive commodity .
On the ICE Futures Exchange , Brent oil futures for November delivery were up 0.33 % and trading at USD115 .41 a barrel , up USD18 .43 from its U.S. counterpart .
